\textbf{\Large Reviewer 1}

\begin{itemize}

\item \textbf{Is there any option to run multiple chains within
  a single command call so that other convergence
  diagnostics such as the Gelman Rubin statistic can
  be computed? Related to this, would it be possible
  to distribute chains to different cores on a
  multiple-cores machine?}

  \medskip

  Yes, we have implemented multiple chain and core processing using the functionality of the
  \pkg{parallel} package. The user can now start models on e.g.\ 3 cores using 2 chains by typing
  \begin{Schunk}
  \begin{Sinput}
  library("R2BayesX")
  ## generate some data
  set.seed(111)
  n <- 500
     
  ## regressors
  dat <- data.frame(x = runif(n, -3, 3), z = runif(n, -3, 3),
    w = runif(n, 0, 6), fac = factor(rep(1:10, n/10)))
     
  ## response
  dat$y <- with(dat, 1.5 + sin(x) + cos(z) * sin(w) +
    c(2.67, 5, 6, 3, 4, 2, 6, 7, 9, 7.5)[fac] + rnorm(n, sd = 0.6))
     
  ## estimate model
  b <- bayesx(y ~ sx(x) + sx(z, w, bs = "te") + fac,
    data = dat, method = "MCMC", chains = 2, cores = 3)
  \end{Sinput}
  \end{Schunk}
  The object \code{b} is also of class \code{"bayesx"} for which all e.g.\ plotting and extractor
  functions may be applied. We have also adapted the \fct{samples} extractor function, which by
  default returns objects of class \code{"mcmc"} or \code{"mcmc.list"} when multiple chains are run.
  In addition, we have implemented a convenience function that directly computes the Gelman and
  Rubin's convergence diagnostic using function \code{gelman.diag()} of the \pkg{coda} package.
  E.g., the user may type
  \begin{Schunk}
  \begin{Sinput}
  GRstats(b, term = c("sx(x)", "sx(z,w)"))
  GRstats(b, term = c("linear-samples", "var-samples"))
  ## output not shown
  \end{Sinput}
  \end{Schunk}


