\item \textbf{Not being able to store large objects is an issue
  in R. How does R2BayesX scale up to cope with outputs
  from large (e.g. spatio-temporal) models?}

  \medskip

  As explained in Section~5.3., the model output files generated by \pkg{BayesX} are optimized,
  i.e., only predictions for unique covariate values are computed and read back into \proglang{R}.
  However, the model output for spatio-temporal data with a large number of time intervals could
  still be improved, since locations/coordinates will be replicated in the model output for every
  period prediction. So far, we did not experience any limitations/problems applying spatio-temporal
  models.
  \fixme{Achim, is that sufficient?}


\item \textbf{Although missing data is implicitly discussed in the
  childhood malnutrition example, how are missing data
  generally coded in BayesX/R2BayesX? It is not immediately
  clear by looking at the data (ZambiaNutrition).}

  \medskip

  \fixme{Achim, I suppose that the \code{na.action} argument is sufficient?}
  Missing data is processed by the \code{na.action} argument in \fct{bayesx}/\fct{parse.bayesx.input}.
  The default in \fct{bayesx} is \code{na.action = NULL}, which means that the function that is
  provided within the \fct{options} setting will be used, the default here is \fct{na.omit}.
  \pkg{BayesX} will then process on the data that is provided from \proglang{R}. In general,
  the \pkg{BayesX} binary will remove all \code{NA}s. \fixme{Stefan/Thomas, is that true?}
 

